<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="258" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1842,2013]" pageId="7" pageNumber="258">
Distribution: Indian records: Himachal Pradesh, Meghalaya, Uttarakhand, West Bengal. Global records: 
<collectingCountry box="[1355,1436,1915,1941]" name="Bhutan" pageId="7" pageNumber="258">Bhutan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Tindale, N. B." box="[205,358,1951,1977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="258" pagination="15 - 46" refId="ref12420" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1941) Revision of the ghost moths (Lepidoptera Homoneura, family Hepialidae). Part IV. Records of the South Australian Museum, 7, 15 - 46." type="journal article" year="1941">Tindale 1941</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Grehan, J. R. &amp; Ismavel, V. A." box="[370,644,1951,1977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="258" pagination="9940 - 9955" refId="ref8690" refString="Grehan, J. R. &amp; Ismavel, V. A. (2017) Forest ghost moth fauna of northeastern India (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae: Endoclita, Palpifer, and Hepialiscus). Journal of Threatened Taxa, 9 (3), 9940 - 9955. https: // doi. org / 10.11609 / jott. 3030.9.3.9940 - 9955" type="journal article" year="2017">Grehan &amp; Ismavel 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="259" pageId="7" pageNumber="258" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1842,2013]" lastBlockId="8.[198,1436,151,249]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="259" pageId="7" pageNumber="258">
Note: The distribution of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[438,584,1987,2012]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Palpifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexnotatus">
<emphasis box="[438,584,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="258">P. sexnotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite dubious. 
<bibRefCitation author="Grehan, J. R. &amp; Ismavel, V. A." box="[784,1074,1987,2013]" pageId="7" pageNumber="258" pagination="9940 - 9955" refId="ref8690" refString="Grehan, J. R. &amp; Ismavel, V. A. (2017) Forest ghost moth fauna of northeastern India (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae: Endoclita, Palpifer, and Hepialiscus). Journal of Threatened Taxa, 9 (3), 9940 - 9955. https: // doi. org / 10.11609 / jott. 3030.9.3.9940 - 9955" type="journal article" year="2017">Grehan &amp; Ismavel (2017)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the Indian distribution of this species from Himachal Pradesh, Meghalaya, Uttarakhand and West Bengal. While, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tindale, N. B." box="[1229,1396,151,177]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" pagination="15 - 46" refId="ref12420" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1941) Revision of the ghost moths (Lepidoptera Homoneura, family Hepialidae). Part IV. Records of the South Australian Museum, 7, 15 - 46." type="journal article" year="1941">Tindale (1941)</bibRefCitation>
reported it from 
<collectingCountry box="[361,446,187,213]" name="Bhutan" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">Bhutan</collectingCountry>
. Dr. J. R. Grehan (per. Comm.) mentioned that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[980,1126,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Palpifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexnotatus">
<emphasis box="[980,1126,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">P. sexnotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is applicable only to northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[284,345,223,249]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">India</collectingCountry>
. So, probably the other records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[731,877,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Palpifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexnotatus">
<emphasis box="[731,877,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">P. sexnotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belong to different species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
